RAPM:
RAP (RESTful ABAP Programming Model) topics in SAP, along with definitions, and how they connect to full-stack development. I’ll break it down clearly so you can understand both the SAP-specific concepts and the broader full-stack picture.
What is RAP in SAP?
RAP (RESTful ABAP Programming Model) is a modern framework in SAP used to build cloud-ready, OData-based business applications using ABAP.

In simple terms:
RAP helps you build end-to-end SAP applications (backend + frontend integration) in a structured, standardized way.
Core RAP Topics (with Definitions)
1. CDS Views (Core Data Services)
Define data models at the database level.
Used to expose data in a structured way.
Think of it as:
Database layer + business semantics

2. Behavior Definition (BDEF)
Defines how data behaves (CRUD operations: Create, Read, Update, Delete).
Controls business logic like validations, actions.
Example:
Allow creating sales orders, but restrict deletion.
3. Behavior Implementation (BIMP)
ABAP class where actual logic is written.
Implements rules defined in Behavior Definition.

Think of it as:
Backend logic execution layer
4. Service Definition
Exposes CDS views as services.
It answers:
“What data should be available to the outside world?”
5. Service Binding
Makes services accessible via OData (V2/V4).
This is what connects SAP backend to UI/frontend apps.
6. Projection Views
A filtered or simplified version of CDS views.
Used to control what the UI sees.

7. Managed vs Unmanaged RAP
Managed RAP
SAP handles CRUD automatically.
Less coding required.
Unmanaged RAP

Developer handles everything manually.
More flexibility.
8. Draft Handling
Allows users to save incomplete data (like drafts in forms).
Example:
Saving a half-filled order before final submission.

9. Locking & Authorization
Controls:
Who can access data
Prevents conflicts (multiple users editing same record)
10. ETag & Concurrency Control
Ensures data consistency when multiple users update data.
11. Actions & Determinations
Actions → User-triggered operations
Determination - Automatically triggered logic
Example:
Action: Approve Order
Determination: Auto-calculated total price
12. Validations
Ensures data correctness before saving.
 Example:
Price cannot be negative.
 RAP Architecture (Simple View)
Database Layer → CDS Views
      ↓
Business Logic → Behavior Definition + Implementation
      ↓
Service Layer → Service Definition + Binding
      ↓
UI Layer → SAP Fiori / External Apps
