The ABAP RESTful Application Programming Model (RAP) is SAP's modern framework for building cloud-ready, transactional business applications, services, and extensions on SAP BTP ABAP Environment, SAP S/4HANA Cloud, and on-premise S/4HANA. It provides a standardized development flow for creating OData-based services, enabling Fiori apps, and managing business objects, leveraging ABAP Core Data Services (CDS) for data modeling. 

Core Topics and Pillars of RAP
•	Data Modeling (CDS): Core Data Services (CDS) is the cornerstone for defining semantically rich data models, including database tables, CDS views, associations, and projections.
•	Behavior Modeling & Implementation: Defines how data can be acted upon. It separates behavior definition (what can be done) from behavior implementation (how it is done in ABAP).
o	Managed Scenario: RAP automatically handles CRUD (Create, Update, Delete) operations, reducing code requirements.
o	Unmanaged Scenario: Used for greenfield/brownfield projects to leverage existing business logic (BAPIs/function modules).
•	Business Object (BO) Structure: Defines real-world entities (e.g., Sales Order) with nodes, standard operations (create/update/delete), and non-standard actions.
•	Entity Manipulation Language (EML): An SQL-like ABAP syntax used to manipulate transactional behavior of RAP BOs within ABAP code.
•	Service Exposure (OData & Fiori): RAP defines services through service definitions and bindings, exposing data and behavior as OData v2 or v4 for Fiori UIs or external Web APIs
	
